Interesting response. I have lost several recordings also. Like you say, 
they just seem to disappear. I thought that maybe I was doing something 
wrong. It is interesting to see that someone else has had the same 
experience.

I use an Olympus digital voice recorder and have no problems with it. As 
for the original post, I never used to get anything when I first 
started. Now it is hit or miss.

Mick

Allen wrote:

&gt; I use a couple different digital voice recorders, but have recorded
&gt; most of my good EVP&#39;s with a Sony ICD-P320 just using the internal
&gt; microphone. Some feel you need to use an external microphone, but I
&gt; tend to set the recorder down and let it do it&#39;s thing. I get more
&gt; EVP&#39;s when it is just sitting there unattended or if we are talking
&gt; about random stuff than I do if asking questions. I cannot hold my
&gt; recorders still enough in my hands to not get noise. An external
&gt; microphone would help that, but I would rather just set the recorder
&gt; down. Maybe some day I will get one and give it a try.
&gt;
&gt; The last investigation we went on, I got 12 good EVP&#39;s. Most were
&gt; short single word recordings, but they required no processing other
&gt; than a volume adjustment on a couple of the quieter ones. Other
&gt; investigations I get nothing. We would have activity, but nothing
&gt; would be recorded. Also, I have recorded stuff only to have it
&gt; disappear off the recorder or computer. Guess someone didn&#39;t want it
&gt; to be shared.
&gt;
&gt; Topics to talk about that seem to draw out the spirits are food,
&gt; alcohol, drugs and smoking. Guess some of the spirits miss them and
&gt; if given a chance will join in and let you know their feelings. I
&gt; haven&#39;t tried talking about sex, but if the other topics work, it
&gt; might also. I don&#39;t think there is anything magic about getting
&gt; EVP&#39;s. It is just a matter of being around someone with something to
&gt; say. Also, I don&#39;t think the location really has that much to do with
&gt; it either. I can get recording from my house almost as easily as a
&gt; &quot;haunted&quot; location. To me, the negative spirits tend to be more vocal
&gt; but will give false information just to mess with you. I believe
&gt; little if anything I record, but simply use it as evidence of
&gt; activity.
&gt;
&gt; I prefer digital for the ease of distributing and archiving
&gt; recordings. The only editing I do is adjusting the gain and cutting
&gt; out parts of the recording that catch my interest. As a personal
&gt; preference, I throw out any EVP&#39;s that need any filtering or
&gt; manipulation to hear. If it can&#39;t be heard as it is (excluding volume
&gt; adjustments), I don&#39;t use it. I promise I am not trying to start an
&gt; argument. As I said, it is just a personal preference.
&gt;
&gt; One of the best recordings I have was from my camcorder. We could
&gt; also hear the spirit talking with our ears and were able to briefly
&gt; have two-way interaction. The funny thing is, when asked a question,
&gt; the three of us present heard it say &quot;yes&quot;, but on the audio, it
&gt; clearly said &quot;no&quot;.
&gt;
&gt; Allen
&gt; www.paranormalsource.com
&gt;
&gt;  


-- 
If you have an interest in the paranormal then check out:
http://www.myspace.com/micksghosts


